  "answer": "The critic misreads the target’s claim. The target does not assert that Egyptian mortuary temple construction was materially modest in absolute terms; it asserts that pharaonic ideology was *less materially intensive* than the competitive gift-exchange systems of peer-polity elites *in the specific structural sense that generated runaway contradictions*. The Ramesseum and Medinet Habu were vast, but they were funded through a redistributive divine-kingship model that channelled surplus into a single, central, ritually self-legitimating circuit rather than into an escalating, multi-polity arms race of reciprocal prestige goods. In the Mycenaean and Hittite spheres, conspicuous consumption was inherently relational and competitive: each elite’s status display demanded a counter-display from rivals, creating an open-ended, accelerating demand for bronze, exotica, and craft labour that the target argues became fiscally unsustainable when supply chains faltered. Egypt’s mortuary endowments, by contrast, were ideologically closed: they demonstrated the pharaoh’s unique divine status rather than competing with equals, and they were materially sustained by permanent land donations and corvée obligations that did not depend on volatile long-distance gift-exchange networks. The critic’s cited examples therefore do not contradict the target’s mechanism—they merely show that Egypt also spent heavily, without addressing whether that spending was structurally competitive and fiscally destabilising in the same way. The target’s distinction is qualitative (competitive vs. non-competitive ideological consumption), not a denial of Egyptian material intensity, so the objection fails to engage the actual argument."
